WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:15.620
We're at a critical moment.
我们正处在一个关键时刻。

2
00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:17.676
Our leaders,
我们的领导者，

3
00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:19.756
some of our great institutions
一些重要的机构

4
00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:20.980
are failing us.
正在辜负我们的期待。

5
00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:23.260
Why?
为什么？

6
00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.356
In some cases, it's because they're bad
在某些案例中，因为他们心怀不轨

7
00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:27.580
or unethical,
或违背了职业道德，

8
00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:32.260
but often, they've taken us to the wrong objectives.
但通常是因为他们把我们 带向了错误的目标。

9
00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:35.540
And this is unacceptable.
而这是让人无法接受的。

10
00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:39.500
This has to stop.
这样的情况应当到此为止。

11
00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:43.020
How are we going to correct these wrongs?
我们该如何纠正这些错误？

12
00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:46.380
How are we going to choose the right course?
我们该如何选择正确的道路？

13
00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:48.460
It's not going to be easy.
这并非易事。

14
00:00:49.660 --> 00:00:51.700
For years, I've worked with talented teams
多年来我一直在与杰出的团队共事，

15
00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:55.556
and they've chosen the right objectives and the wrong objectives.
他们或在正确的道路上前进， 或选错了目标而事与愿违。

16
00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:58.196
Many have succeeded, others of them have failed.
许多目标成功达成了，有些则遭遇了失败。

17
00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:00.436
And today I'm going to share with you
今天我要和你分享的是

18
00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:02.756
what really makes a difference --
真正能够带来改变的事情——

19
00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:05.196
that's what's crucial,
即问题的关键所在，

20
00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:06.756
how and why
他们为何以及如何

21
00:01:06.780 --> 00:01:09.316
they set meaningful and audacious goals,
制定出有意义的、大胆的目标，

22
00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:11.980
the right goals for the right reasons.
即有正当理由的，正确的目标。

23
00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:15.716
Let's go back to 1975.
让我们回到1975年。

24
00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:17.356
Yep, this is me.
没错，这就是我。

25
00:01:17.380 --> 00:01:19.716
I've got a lot to learn, I'm a computer engineer,
当时我是个计算机工程师， 还有很多东西要学。

26
00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:20.996
I've got long hair,
我留着长发，

27
00:01:20.906 --> 00:01:22.940
but I'm working under Andy Grove,
在安迪 · 葛洛夫手下工作，

28
00:01:24.020 --> 00:01:28.316
who's been called the greatest manager of his or any other era.
在任何时代，他都 称得上是最伟大的管理者。

29
00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:32.316
Andy was a superb leader and also a teacher,
安迪不仅是一流的领导者，也是一名导师。

30
00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:35.660
and he said to me, "John, it almost doesn't matter what you know.
他曾对我说：“约翰， 你所知道的东西并不重要，

31
00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:39.596
Execution is what matters the most."
执行才是最重要的。”

32
00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:44.356
And so Andy invented a system called "Objectives and Key Results."
安迪发明了一个系统， 称为“目标和关键成果法”。

33
00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:46.460
It kind of rolls off the tongue, doesn't it?
听起来是不是有点绕口？

34
00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:51.036
And it's all about excellent execution.
其核心全在于出色的执行。

35
00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:54.036
So here's a classic video from the 1970s
以下是一段1970年代的经典录像，

36
00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.596
of professor Andy Grove.
录像里出现的就是安迪 · 葛洛夫教授。

37
00:01:56.620 --> 00:02:00.316
(Video) Andy Grove: The two key phrases of the management by objective systems
（录像）安迪 · 葛洛夫： 这种目标管理的两个关键词是

38
00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:04.116
are the objectives and the key results, and they match the two purposes.
“目标”和“关键成果”， 它们分别对应着两个目的：

39
00:02:04.140 --> 00:02:07.356
The objective is the direction.
目标是方向，

40
00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:09.116
The key results have to be measured,
关键成果需要得到评估，

41
00:02:09.140 --> 00:02:11.836
but at the end you can look and without any argument say,
但是最终结果显而易见，根本不需要出现

42
00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:14.636
"Did I do that, or did I not do that?" Yes. No. Simple.
“我做了这个吗，或者根本没做？” 那样的争论，是或否，就是这么简单。

43
00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:16.076
John Doerr: That's Andy.
约翰 · 杜尔：这就是安迪。

44
00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.140
Yes. No. Simple.
是或否，就是这么简单。

45
00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:21.555
Objectives and Key Results,
目标和关键成果法

46
00:02:21.579 --> 00:02:23.716
or OKRs,
也称为OKRs，

47
00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:26.236
are a simple goal-setting system
是一个简单的目标制定方法。

48
00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:29.156
and they work for organizations, they work for teams,
它适用于组织还有团队，

49
00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:30.860
they even work for individuals.
甚至也适用于个人。

50
00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:34.596
The objectives are what you want to have accomplished.
目标就是你想实现的事情，

51
00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:37.756
The key results are how I'm going to get that done.
关键成果是你要如何达成目标。

52
00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:40.076
Objectives. Key results.
目标，以及关键成果，

53
00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:41.780
What and how.
就是要做什么和如何实现。

54
00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:44.260
But here's the truth:
但真实的情况是：

55
00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:47.396
many of us are setting goals wrong,
我们中有许多人都制定了错误的目标，

56
00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:49.580
and most of us are not setting goals at all.
大多数人甚至完全不设定目标。

57
00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:52.916
A lot of organizations set objectives and meet them.
许多组织机构设定目标并努力实现它们。

58
00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:55.956
They ship their sales, they introduce their new products,
这些组织发货，研发新产品，

59
00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:57.476
they make their numbers,
他们不断获得收益，

60
00:02:57.500 --> 00:03:01.980
but they lack a sense of purpose to inspire their teams.
但缺少激励团队的使命感。

61
00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:04.660
So how do you set these goals the right way?
那么该如何正确地设定目标呢？

62
00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:08.900
First, you must answer the question, "Why?"
首先你必须回答一个问题：“为什么？”

63
00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:10.916
Why?
为什么这么问？

64
00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:13.676
Because truly transformational teams
因为真正变革型的团队

65
00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:18.876
combine their ambitions to their passion and to their purpose,
都会将自己的雄心、 热情和目标结合到一起。

66
00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:21.700
and they develop a clear and compelling sense of why.
他们很清楚为何要做，且理由令人信服。

67
00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:24.386
I want to tell you a story.
我想要告诉大家一个故事，

68
00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:27.316
I work with a remarkable entrepreneur.
有一位与我共事的出色的企业家，

69
00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:28.820
Her name is Jini Kim.
她的名词是金基妮(Jini Kim)。

70
00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:31.220
She runs a company called Nuna.
她运营着一家公司，叫做Nuna。

71
00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:34.500
Nuna is a health care data company.
这是一家健康护理数据公司。

72
00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:37.436
And when Nuna was founded,
公司初创时，

73
00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:42.140
they used data to serve the health needs of lots of workers at large companies.
他们使用数据为大企业的 很多员工提供健康服务。

74
00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:45.236
And then two years into the company's life,
公司成立两年后，

75
00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:47.836
the federal government issued a proposal
联邦政府发布了一项提案，

76
00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:51.020
to build the first ever cloud database for Medicaid.
要成立首个用于医疗救助 制度的云数据库。

77
00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:54.356
Now, you'll remember that Medicaid is that program
你们知道医疗救助制度

78
00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:56.836
that serves 70 million Americans,
为7千万美国人服务，

79
00:03:56.860 --> 00:03:58.500
our poor, our children
包括贫困人群，儿童，

80
00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:00.940
and people with disabilities.
以及残障人士。

81
00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:06.036
Nuna at the time was just 15 people
Nuna公司在当时只有15个人，

82
00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:08.716
and this database had to be built in one year,
这个数据库要在一年内建成，

83
00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:12.356
and they had a whole set of commitments that they had to honor,
他们有一系列承诺需要履行。

84
00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:15.740
and frankly, they weren't going to make very much money on the project.
坦白讲，这个项目 并不能让他们大赚一笔。

85
00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:19.796
This was a bet-your-company moment,
这是赌上公司的时刻，

86
00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:21.236
and Jini seized it.
而基妮把握住了它。

87
00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:24.180
She jumped at the opportunity. She did not flinch.
她扑向了这个机会，她没有退缩。

88
00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:26.820
Why?
为什么？

89
00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:29.516
Well, it's a personal why.
这事关个人原因。

90
00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:32.540
Jini's younger brother Kimong has autism.
基妮的弟弟津孟(Kimong)患有自闭症，

91
00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.116
And when he was seven,
在七岁时，

92
00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:38.396
he had his first grand mal seizure
他第一次发病

93
00:04:38.420 --> 00:04:39.636
at Disneyland.
是在迪士尼乐园。

94
00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:42.116
He fell to the ground. He stopped breathing.
他倒在地上，停止了呼吸。

95
00:04:42.140 --> 00:04:44.836
Jini's parents are Korean immigrants.
基妮的父母都是韩裔移民，

96
00:04:44.860 --> 00:04:48.236
They came to the country with limited resources
他们身无长物来到这个国家，

97
00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:50.116
speaking little English,
也不太会讲英语，

98
00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.140
so it was up to Jini to enroll her family in Medicaid.
所以只能靠基妮 帮家人加入医疗救助系统。

99
00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:55.620
She was nine years old.
她当时只有九岁。

100
00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.196
That moment defined her mission,
这个重大时刻决定了她的使命，

101
00:05:01.220 --> 00:05:03.916
and that mission became her company,
而这项使命成就了她公司，

102
00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:07.180
and that company bid on, won and delivered on that contract.
这家公司竞标，赢得并实现了这个合同。

103
00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:10.636
Here's Jini to tell you why.
让基妮来告诉你她这样做的原因。

104
00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:13.476
(Video) Jini Kim: Medicaid saved my family from bankruptcy,
（视频）金基妮：医疗救助 使我的家庭免于破产，

105
00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:17.020
and today it provides for Kimong's health and for millions of others.
如今它为津孟和其他 数百万患者提供健康服务。

106
00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:20.196
Nuna is my love letter to Medicaid.
Nuna是我给医疗救助的一封情书。

107
00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:22.036
Every row of data is a life
每一条数据都是一个生命，

108
00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:24.300
whose story deserves to be told with dignity.
它的故事需要有尊严地被讲述。

109
00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:27.516
JD: And Jini's story tells us
约翰 · 杜尔：基妮的故事告诉我们，

110
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:32.516
that a compelling sense of why can be the launchpad for our objectives.
一种极具说服力的原因 能够成为目标的发射平台。

111
00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:35.716
Remember, that's what we want to have accomplished.
要记得，这是我们想要达成的事情。

112
00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:38.356
And objectives are significant,
目标是重要的，

113
00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:40.276
they're action-oriented,
它们以行动为指向，

114
00:05:40.300 --> 00:05:42.260
they are inspiring,
它们激励人心，

115
00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:45.780
and they're a kind of vaccine against fuzzy thinking.
是对抗纷乱思绪的一针疫苗。

116
00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:47.876
You think a rockstar
你以为一个摇滚明星，

117
00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:51.436
would be an unlikely user of Objectives and Key Results,
不太可能使用目标成果法，

118
00:05:51.460 --> 00:05:54.276
but for years, Bono has used OKRs
但是数年以来， 博诺（Bono）通过使用OKRs

119
00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:58.596
to wage a global war against poverty and disease,
掀起了一场对抗贫穷和 疾病的全球战争。

120
00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:02.836
and his ONE organization has focused on two really gorgeous,
他的One组织专注在两个目标上，

121
00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:04.676
audacious objectives.
它们非常棒，也非常大胆。

122
00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.996
The first is debt relief
第一个目标

123
00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.020
for the poorest countries in the world.
是为世界上最贫穷的国家减轻债务；

124
00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:14.716
The next is universal access to anti-HIV drugs.
第二个则是普及抗艾滋病药物。

125
00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:16.716
Now, why are these good objectives?
如今，这些目标完成的怎么样了？

126
00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:18.756
Let's go back to our checklist.
让我们回到我们的检查清单。

127
00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:22.156
Significant? Check. Concrete? Yes.
这些目标重要么？是的。 这些目标具体么？是的。

128
00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:23.996
Action-oriented? Yes.
它们以行动为导向么？是的。

129
00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:25.220
Inspirational?
是否激励人心？

130
00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:27.700
Well, let's just listen to Bono.
还是让我们听听博诺怎么说。

131
00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:30.036
(Video) Bono: So you're passionate?
（视频）博诺：你有热情么？

132
00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:31.276
How passionate?
有多大热情？

133
00:06:31.300 --> 00:06:33.740
What actions does your passion lead you to do?
你的热情引导出了你的什么行动？

134
00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:37.476
If the heart doesn't find a perfect rhyme with the head,
如果内心找不到与大脑和谐的韵律，

135
00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:39.716
then your passion means nothing.
你的热情就毫无用处。

136
00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:43.276
The OKR framework cultivates the madness,
OKRs框架可以培养出疯狂的想法，

137
00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:45.676
the chemistry contained inside it.
里面包含着化学火花。

138
00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:47.836
It gives us an environment for risk,
它给了我们一个环境，为了风险，

139
00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:49.076
for trust,
为了信任，

140
00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:51.476
where failing is not a fireable offense.
在这里，失败不是可怕的犯罪。

141
00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:54.120
And when you have that sort of structure and environment
当你有了这种结构和环境，

142
00:06:54.144 --> 00:06:55.876
and the right people,
加上对的人，

143
00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:58.590
magic is around the corner.
奇迹就会出现。

144
00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:01.916
JD: I love that.
约翰 · 杜尔：我很喜欢这段话，

145
00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.316
OKRs cultivate the madness,
OKRs培养出疯狂的想法，

146
00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:07.076
and magic is right around the corner.
奇迹就会出现。

147
00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:08.300
This is perfect.
这简直完美。

148
00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:12.876
So with Jini we've covered the whys,
通过基妮，我们看到了原因，

149
00:07:12.900 --> 00:07:15.716
with Bono the whats of goal-setting.
通过博诺，我们了解了目标设定。

150
00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:18.276
Let's turn our attention to the hows.
让我们再来关注方法。

151
00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:20.516
Remember, the hows are the key results.
如何做是关键结果。

152
00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:22.876
That's how we meet our objectives.
这就是我们实现目标的方法。

153
00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:25.476
And good results are specific and time-bound.
好的结果是明确且有时间限制的。

154
00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:27.476
They're aggressive but realistic.
它们很激进但也很现实，

155
00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:29.556
They're measurable, and they're verifiable.
它们可衡量也可评估，

156
00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:31.140
Those are good key results.
这就是好的关键成果。

157
00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:37.076
In 1999, I introduced OKRs to Google's cofounders,
1999年，我向谷歌的 联合创始人拉里和谢尔盖

158
00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:38.356
Larry and Sergey.
介绍了OKRs。

159
00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:41.716
Here they are, 24 years old in their garage.
这是24岁时的他们在自家的车库里。

160
00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:44.180
And Sergey enthusiastically said he'd adopt them.
谢尔盖充满热情地说打算采用这个方法。

161
00:07:45.620 --> 00:07:47.300
Well, not quite.
然而，确切地说，

162
00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:49.716
What he really said was,
他真正说的是：

163
00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:52.196
"We don't have any other way to manage this company,
“我们没有其他的方法来管理这家公司，

164
00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:53.476
so we'll give it a go."
所以不如试一下。“

165
00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:54.716
(Laughter)
（笑声）

166
00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:57.100
And I took that as a kind of endorsement.
我将其视为某种认可。

167
00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.476
But every quarter since then,
从那之后的每个季度，

168
00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:04.940
every Googler has written down her objectives and her key results.
每一个谷歌人写下的目标和关键成果，

169
00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:07.076
They've graded them,
都会得到他们的评价，

170
00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:09.300
and they've published them for everyone to see.
然后公布给每个人看。

171
00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:13.196
And these are not used for bonuses or for promotions.
这些内容并不被用于奖金或升职，

172
00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:14.516
They're set aside.
就是摆在那里，

173
00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:16.276
They're used for a higher purpose,
用于实现更高的目标——

174
00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:18.396
and that's to get collective commitment
那就是获取共同责任感

175
00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:19.900
to truly stretch goals.
以真正推动目标。

176
00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:26.276
In 2008, a Googler, Sundar Pichai, took on an objective
在2008年，谷歌员工 桑达尔 · 皮查伊设定了一个目标，

177
00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:29.596
which was to build the next generation client platform
他要为未来的网络应用

178
00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.460
for the future of web applications --
建立下一代客户平台。

179
00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:35.140
in other words, build the best browser.
换句话说，就是打造一个最好的浏览器。

180
00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:39.180
He was very thoughtful about how he chose his key results.
在选择关键结果上，| 他有着非常深入的思考。

181
00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:41.476
How do you measure the best browser?
如何来衡量这是最好的浏览器？

182
00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:43.596
It could be ad clicks or engagement.
可以参考广告点击和用户参与度。

183
00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:47.276
No. He said: numbers of users,
不，他认为是用户数量，

184
00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:49.355
because users are going to decide
因为用户会决定

185
00:08:49.379 --> 00:08:51.796
if Chrome is a great browser or not.
Chrome浏览器是好还是坏。

186
00:08:51.820 --> 00:08:55.396
So he had this one three-year-long objective:
因此他定下了这个长达三年的目标：

187
00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:56.676
build the best browser.
打造最好的浏览器。

188
00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:59.676
And then every year he stuck to the same key results,
之后的每一年，他都会 专注于相同的关键成果，

189
00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:01.636
numbers of users, but he upped the ante.
即用户数量，但是要求不断提高。

190
00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:03.916
In the first year, his goal was 20 million users
在最初一年，他的目标是2000万用户，

191
00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:05.476
and he missed it.
但并没有达成。

192
00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:06.756
He got less than 10.
用户数量还不到1000万。

193
00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:09.596
Second year, he raised the bar to 50 million.
第二年，他把目标提高到5000万。

194
00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:11.756
He got to 37 million users.
结果用户数量达到 3700 万。

195
00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:13.020
Somewhat better.
不管怎样，总算有些进步。

196
00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:14.820
In the third year,
在第三年，

197
00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.756
he upped the ante once more to a hundred million.
他再次将目标提高到1亿。

198
00:09:18.780 --> 00:09:21.236
He launched an aggressive marketing campaign,
他启动了一个激进的营销活动，

199
00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:24.716
broader distribution, improved the technology, and kaboom!
采用更广泛的推广手段， 改善的技术，用户数量终于爆发了！

200
00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:27.180
He got 111 million users.
他获得了1.11亿用户。

201
00:09:28.420 --> 00:09:30.276
Here's why I like this story,
我之所以喜欢这个故事，

202
00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:32.116
not so much for the happy ending,
并不在于它有圆满的大结局，

203
00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:36.156
but it shows someone carefully choosing the right objective
而是它表现出一个人 仔细选择了正确的目标，

204
00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:39.300
and then sticking to it year after year after year.
并年复一年始终坚持下来。

205
00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:42.140
It's a perfect story for a nerd like me.
对我这样的书呆子来说， 这简直是个完美的故事。

206
00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:47.636
Now, I think of OKRs as transparent vessels
我把OKRs看做是一个透明容器，

207
00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.660
that are made from the whats and hows of our ambitions.
它由野心勃勃的“做什么” 和“怎么做”构成。

208
00:09:52.540 --> 00:09:57.996
What really matters is the why that we pour into those vessels.
真正的关键在于 放进容器中的“为什么”，

209
00:09:57.980 --> 00:09:59.660
That's why we do our work.
那是我们工作的原因。

210
00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:02.060
OKRs are not a silver bullet.
OKRs并非万能良药。

211
00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.836
They're not going to be a substitute for a strong culture
它无法代替强有力的文化

212
00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:07.756
or for stronger leadership,
或是强有力的领导力。

213
00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:11.500
but when those fundamentals are in place, they can take you to the mountaintop.
但当这些基本元素都就位， 它们就可以带你走上巅峰。

214
00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:15.300
I want you to think about your life for a moment.
现在，我希望你们 思考一下自己的生活。

215
00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:17.940
Do you have the right metrics?
你是否拥有正确的衡量标准？

216
00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:23.396
Take time to write down your values,
花点时间写下你认为有价值的东西，

217
00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:26.460
your objectives and your key results.
你的目标和关键成果。

218
00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:28.220
Do it today.
今天就行动。

219
00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:31.916
If you'd like some feedback on them, you can send them to me.
如果你想获得反馈，可以将它发给我。

220
00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:34.180
I'm john@whatmatters.com.
我的邮箱地址是： john@whatmatters.com

221
00:10:35.540 --> 00:10:38.676
If we think of the world-changing goals
如果我们想想那些改变世界的目标，

222
00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:42.916
of an Intel, of a Nuna, of Bono,
英特尔，Nuna，博诺，

223
00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:44.636
of Google,
还有谷歌的目标，

224
00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:45.916
they're remarkable:
它们都令人惊叹：

225
00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:47.796
ubiquitous computing,
普适计算，

226
00:10:47.820 --> 00:10:51.396
affordable health care, high-quality for everyone,
低价优质的全民医疗，

227
00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:53.076
ending global poverty,
终结全球贫困，

228
00:10:53.100 --> 00:10:55.020
access to all the world's information.
获取全球信息。

229
00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:57.156
Here's the deal:
事实情况是，

230
00:10:57.180 --> 00:11:01.620
every one of those goals is powered today by OKRs.
每个目标都得到了OKRs的助力。

231
00:11:03.100 --> 00:11:06.036
Now, I've been called the Johnny Appleseed of OKRs
现在我被叫做OKRs播种机，

232
00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:09.356
for spreading the good gospel according to Andy Grove,
将安迪 · 葛洛夫的福音传播四方。

233
00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:12.956
but I want you to join me in this movement.
但是我希望你也能参与到这场运动中，

234
00:11:12.980 --> 00:11:15.556
Let's fight for what it is that really matters,
让我们为真正关键的事情而奋斗，

235
00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:19.076
because we can take OKRs beyond our businesses.
因为我们不仅可以 将OKRs运用到商业中，

236
00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:21.036
We can take them to our families,
还可以将其用于家庭，

237
00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:22.316
to our schools,
学校，

238
00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:23.740
even to our governments.
甚至是政府。

239
00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:26.716
We can hold those governments accountable.
我们可以让政府承担责任。

240
00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:28.455
We can transform those informations.
我们可以转化这些信息。

241
00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:31.559
We can get back on the right track
我们可以回到正确的轨道上——

242
00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:41.220
if we can and do measure what really matters.
前提是，我们能够并且 真正去判断关键所在。

243
00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:43.316
Thank you.
谢谢大家。

244
00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:47.220
(Applause)
（掌声）